====Audi in the World Endurance Championship====

In 2012 the FIA sanctioned a [[World Endurance Championship]] which would be organised by the ACO as a continuation of the ILMC. Audi competed won the first WEC race at Sebring and followed this up with a further three successive wins, including the [[2012 24 hours of Le Mans]]. Audi scored a final 5th victory in the 2012 WEC in Bahrain and were able to win the inaugural WEC Manufacturers' Championship.

As defending champions, Audi once again entered the [[R18|Audi R18 e-tron quattro]] chassis into the [[2013 FIA World Endurance Championship season|2013 WEC]] and the team won the first five consecutive races, including the [[2013 24 hours of le Mans]]. The victory at Round 5, [[Circuit of the Americas]], was of particular significance as it marked the 100th win for Audi in Le Mans prototypes.<ref>https://www.audi-mediaservices.com/publish/ms/content/en/public/pressemitteilungen/2013/09/22/audi_celebrates_100th.html</ref>  Audi secured their second consecutive WEC Manufacturers' Championship at Round 6 after taking second place and half points in the red-flagged Fuji race.<ref>http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/110760</ref>

